@mauicartel - January 13, 2018 was heavy. Missile were launched and Bombs detonated in Maui just off the coast of Pe’ahi. Lucky for Hawaii Nei it was bombs like this and not the start of WWIII. And it was Aaron Gold on a hand shaped rocket who dropped in and blew the whole place up again. Funny (or not so funny) part was we left at dawn and had no clue until we came up from the cliff at 6pm that everyone was scrambling / people going into manholes to seek shelter. Ignorant bliss? Athlete: Aaron Gold / Film: Maui Media Cartel

@kai_lenny - WSL BWT: Stop 1 - Puerto Escondido offered up some big heavy barrels for the start of the Big Wave World Tour. I went into that event wanting to catch two good rides that would get me into the next round. By the end of the day I realized I could win. With perfect timing the wave I had been waiting for finally came to me in during the final and gave me the ride to win the event. I caught so many great waves that day and got smeared on the sand bottom too!
photos: @moralesedwin @derekdunfee @nomadbythesea

Repost @powerlinesproductions - Local Mavz standout @jasonmontara makes the journey over to Portugal yearly to be with his wife's family and get some good surf. He dipped into some Nazaré for the first time and experienced how amazing the place is. Here's a couple of pics by his wife Joana of his sesh.

Here's what Jason said about his sesh:
"What a start to 2018! Thanks to the help of friends and family, I got to realize a paddle session at Nazaré in Portugal yesterday. Thanks Steve Rice for letting me borrow your 11' Pukas, thank you Joana Laranjinha Stark for the photos, and thank you two Ausies (Wish I was better remembering names) for staying out there with me and spotting me on your ski. I definitely owe you some beers next time you roll thru town to surf Mav's . So stoked! This place is so incredible. The wave energy is × 2 or 3 at times, and big shifty beach break is always humbling. So epic and incredibly intimidating. Much respect." @mcnamara_s
@manuel.ricardo.12

Today, has died at age 87, a great Hawaiian legend, the great waterman George Downing.
Was always a visionary and consider by many as a "teacher", in 1950 created the first surfboard with movable fins. Always pushing boundaries in big wave surfing. He devoted a great deal of time to studying the wave predictions, and became for many years, responsible for not only idealizing the legendary and renowned Hawaiian Championship Eddie Aikau, but for saying if the event would happen or not.
A great example of human being and very important in the history of Hawaiian and world surfing!

@rktraininghawaii - The brain has an electrical response witch create brain waves...
Delta is the slowest like a deep sleep...
Theta is a meditation state or insight state...
Alpha is a resting state relaxed, calm, lucid but no really thinking...
Beta signifies learning and concentration at the low end, fear and stress at the high...
And Gamma is when different parts of the brain are combining disparate thoughts into a single idea...
Being able to stay between Alpha and Theta is the only state that can produce Gamma spikes...
At this state will increases our creative decision making abilities...
This experience brings meaningfulness in life, sense of purpose, self determination, motivation...
To alter brain waves, mindfulness breathing...
Alter your breathing state is your key to get the best of your brain...
